</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="PADDING:0PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;MARGIN-LEFT:10%;">
<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<SUP>
	(1)
</SUP>
</FONT>
</DT>
</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	See
	Note&nbsp;3 to the consolidated financial statements for additional information.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<SUP>
	(2)
</SUP>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Comparable
	sales data is calculated by excluding the net sales of a store for any month of one period if the store was not owned or open
	throughout the same month of the prior period and, beginning in 2013, include e-commerce net sales. We operate our business using an omni-channel approach and do not differentiate e-commerce sales
	from our other channels. Comparable sales percentages for Moores are calculated using Canadian dollars. Comparable sales for Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank are calculated in the same manner as our other brands
	except that it is based on Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank's entire fiscal 2014, a portion of which was prior to our acquisition on June&nbsp;18, 2014.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<SUP>
	(3)
</SUP>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Average
	net sales per square foot is calculated by dividing total square footage for all stores owned or open the entire year into net sales
	for those stores. The calculation for Men's Wearhouse includes Men's Wearhouse and Tux stores. The calculation for Moores is based upon the Canadian dollar. For fiscal 2012, the calculation excludes
	total sales for the 53
<SUP>
	rd
</SUP>
	week.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<SUP>
	(4)
</SUP>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Average
	square footage is calculated by dividing the total square footage for all stores open at the end of the period by the number of stores
	open at the end of such period.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<SUP>
	(5)
</SUP>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	For
	2015 and 2014 excludes 14 and 15&nbsp;franchise stores, respectively.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<SUP>
	(6)
</SUP>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	For
	2015, includes one Joseph Abboud store.
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>

<EFX_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION>
<A NAME="FIS_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION"></A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A NAME="A2227942Z10-K_HTM_DK11901_ITEM_7__MANAGEMENT_S_DISCUSSIO__ITE03668">
</A>
<A NAME="A2227942Z10-K_HTM_TOC_DK11901_2">
</A>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
	ITEM&nbsp;7.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;MANAGEMENT'S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS OF FINANCIAL CONDITION AND RESULTS OF OPERATIONS
<BR>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS207" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#B54A63" SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Executive Overview
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS207" -->
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#B54A63" SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Background
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Effective January&nbsp;31, 2016, Tailored Brands,&nbsp;Inc., a Texas corporation ("Tailored Brands"), became the successor reporting company to
	The Men's Wearhouse,&nbsp;Inc., pursuant to a holding company reorganization. We believe that the holding company structure will allow us to support, nurture and augment our family of brands as we
	further leverage our shared services platform. As a result, beginning in the first quarter of 2016, we implemented legal and operational changes in how we manage our business, including resource
	allocation and performance assessment. In future periods, we expect to report three operating segments: retail, corporate apparel and shared services.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	We
	are the largest specialty retailer of men's suits and the largest provider of rental product in the U.S. and Canada with 1,724&nbsp;stores including tuxedo shops within Macy's stores. Our
	operations are conducted in two reportable segments, retail and corporate apparel, based on the way we manage, evaluate and internally report our business activities. Refer to Item&nbsp;1,
	"Business" of this Annual Report
	on Form&nbsp;10-K as well as Note&nbsp;17 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements and the discussion included in "Results of Operations" below for additional information and disclosures
	regarding our reporting segments.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	On
	June&nbsp;10, 2015, we entered into a 10-year agreement with Macy's,&nbsp;Inc. to operate men's tuxedo rental shops inside 300 Macy's stores. As of January&nbsp;30, 2016, we operated 12
	tuxedo shops within Macy's stores under the name "The Tuxedo Shop&nbsp;@ Macy's." We have refined our Tuxedo Shop&nbsp;@ Macy's rollout schedule and now plan to open 166&nbsp;stores in 2016 with
	the balance of 122&nbsp;stores to be opened in 2017. In addition, we will collaborate with Macy's to develop an online tuxedo rental shop.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	On
	June&nbsp;18, 2014, we acquired 100% of the outstanding common stock of Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank, a men's specialty apparel retailer, for $65.00 net per share in cash, or total consideration of
	approximately $1.8&nbsp;billion. As a result, the comparability of our results is affected by the inclusion of Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank's results for the entire fiscal year ended January&nbsp;30, 2016,
	while last year's operations include Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank's results beginning on June&nbsp;18, 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS207" -->
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#B54A63" SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Summary of Financial Performance
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Our fiscal 2015 operating performance was negatively impacted by (i)&nbsp;goodwill and intangible asset impairment charges related to our
	Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank brand, (ii)&nbsp;restructuring and other charges resulting primarily from our store rationalization program which identified approximately 250&nbsp;stores to be closed in
	fiscal 2016, and (iii)&nbsp;a decrease in revenues and profitability at our Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank brand primarily driven by our decision to remove the most excessive promotional offers (the
	Buy-One-Get-Three Free or more events). In order to mitigate the impact of our decision to remove the most excessive promotional offers at Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank, we introduced new promotional offers
	that do not require excessive quantity purchases and are better aligned with how our customers have told us they prefer to shop. Our customer research indicates while our existing customers appreciate
	our quality and value, many dislike being forced to buy in quantity and many of our prospective Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank customers found our promotional offers confusing and caused them to question the
	quality of our products. By contrast, in fiscal 2015, our Men's Wearhouse/Men's Wearhouse and Tux ("Men's Wearhouse") brand performed well, generating a comparable sales increase of 4.9%, with
	clothing comparable sales of 6.8%, partially offset by a rental service comparable sales decrease of 0.7%.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	35
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>

</FONT>

	compared to operating income of $73.2&nbsp;million in fiscal 2014.
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>

	effect of these items on pretax income for each applicable fiscal year is presented below (dollars in millions):

<!-- ZEQ.=4,SEQ=37,EFW="2227942",CP="TAILORED BRANDS INC",DN="1",CHK=1268,FOLIO='36',FILE='DISK129:[16ZAI1.16ZAI11901]DK11901A.;7',USER='SLYUBOM',CD='24-MAR-2016;12:50' -->
<A NAME="A2227942Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_DK11901_1_37">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2227942Z10-K_HTM_BG11901A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS207" -->
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#B54A63" SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	2016 Initiatives
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	During the fourth quarter of fiscal 2015, we began implementing multiple initiatives intended to reduce costs and improve operating performance.
	These initiatives include a store rationalization program which identified approximately 250&nbsp;stores to be closed as well as a profit improvement program to drive operating efficiencies and
	improve our expense structure. The store rationalization program includes the closure of approximately 80 to 90 Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank full line stores, the closure of all outlet stores at Jos.&nbsp;A.
	Bank and Men's Wearhouse (58&nbsp;stores) and the closure of between 100 and 110 Men's Wearhouse and Tux stores primarily as the result of the rollout of our shops within Macy's stores. We expect
	the store rationalization and profit improvement programs to be completed in fiscal 2016.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	We
	expect the profit improvement program to reduce our expenses by approximately $50.0&nbsp;million in fiscal 2016. This program includes reduced distribution costs, cost reductions in our
	organizational structure, payroll and employee benefit reductions and savings in occupancy and goods-not-for-resale.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	We
	estimate the cash costs to complete the store rationalization and profit improvement programs to be between $45.0 and $60.0&nbsp;million in fiscal 2016, primarily consisting of lease termination
	costs and consulting and severance costs.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS207" -->
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#B54A63" SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Store Information
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	During fiscal 2015, we opened 42&nbsp;stores/tuxedo shops (18 Men's Wearhouse stores, 12&nbsp;shops within Macy's stores, eight Jos.&nbsp;A.
	Bank stores, two Moores stores, one Joseph Abboud store and one K&amp;G store) and closed 76&nbsp;stores (50 Men's Wearhouse and Tux stores, 19 Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank stores, three Men's Wearhouse stores,
	three K&amp;G stores and one Moores store).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	In
	fiscal 2016, we plan to open 166&nbsp;shops within Macy's stores, 15 to 20 Men's Wearhouse stores, three Moores stores, two Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank stores and two K&amp;G stores and to expand and/or
	relocate approximately 8 to 12 existing Men's Wearhouse stores, four to eight existing Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank stores and one existing K&amp;G store. We also plan to close 130 to 140 Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank
	stores, 100 to 110 Men's Wearhouse and Tux stores and 10 Men's Wearhouse stores.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	37
</FONT>
</P>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<SUP>
	(1)
</SUP>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Percentage
	line items may not sum to totals due to the effect of rounding.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<SUP>
	(2)
</SUP>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Calculated
	as a percentage of related sales.
</FONT>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2227942Z10-K_HTM_BG11901A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents

</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS207" -->
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#B54A63" SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	2015 Compared with 2014
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Net Sales
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Total net sales increased $243.7&nbsp;million, or 7.5%, to $3,496.3&nbsp;million for fiscal 2015 as compared to fiscal 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Total
	retail sales increased $257.3&nbsp;million, or 8.6%, to $3,252.5&nbsp;million for fiscal 2015 as compared to fiscal 2014 due mainly to $182.9&nbsp;million of incremental net sales from
	Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank, as fiscal 2015 includes full year results from Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank while fiscal 2014 represented results only from the date of acquisition. Total retail sales also increased due
	to retail clothing product and alteration revenues from our other brands of $81.2&nbsp;million partially offset by a decrease in rental services revenue from our other brands of $8.3&nbsp;million.
	The net increase is attributable to the following:
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="PADDING:0PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;WIDTH:80%;MARGIN-LEFT:10%;">
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
</FONT>
</P>

<!-- COMMAND=ADD_LINERULETXT,NOSHADE COLOR="#000000" SIZE="1.0PT" WIDTH="26%" ALIGN="LEFT" -->
<HR NOSHADE COLOR="#000000" SIZE="1.0PT" WIDTH="26%" ALIGN="LEFT">
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="PADDING:0PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;MARGIN-LEFT:10%;">
<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<SUP>
	(1)
</SUP>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Comparable
	sales percentages for Moores are calculated using Canadian dollars.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<SUP>
	(2)
</SUP>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Excludes
	Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank.
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Comparable
	sales for Men's Wearhouse, Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank, Moores and K&amp;G exclude the net sales of a store for any month of one period if the store was not open throughout the same month of the prior
	period and include e-commerce net sales. We operate our business using an omni-channel approach and do not differentiate e-commerce sales from our other channels.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The
	increase at Men's Wearhouse resulted primarily from increased average unit retails (net selling prices) and average transactions per store that more than offset decreased units sold per
	transaction. The decrease at Moores was driven by decreased average transactions per store and units sold per transaction that more than offset increased average unit retails. The increase at K&amp;G was
	driven by increased average transactions per store and units sold per transaction while average unit retails were flat. At Men's Wearhouse, rental service comparable sales decreased 0.7% primarily due
	to a decrease in unit rentals partially offset by an increase in rental rates.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Comparable
	sales for Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank decreased by 16.4% and are calculated in the same manner as our other brands except that it is based on Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank's entire fiscal 2014, a portion of
	which was prior to our acquisition on June&nbsp;18, 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Total
	corporate apparel clothing product sales decreased $13.6&nbsp;million to $243.8&nbsp;million for fiscal 2015 as compared to fiscal 2014. UK corporate apparel sales decreased
	$11.7&nbsp;million due to unfavorable currency fluctuations this year compared to last year. U.S. corporate apparel sales decreased $1.9&nbsp;million due primarily to decreased sales from existing
	customer programs.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	39
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=2,SEQ=40,EFW="2227942",CP="TAILORED BRANDS INC",DN="1",CHK=305772,FOLIO='39',FILE='DISK129:[16ZAI1.16ZAI11901]DM11901A.;20',USER='SLYUBOM',CD='24-MAR-2016;12:55' -->
<A NAME="A2227942Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_DM11901_1_40">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2227942Z10-K_HTM_BG11901A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Gross Margin
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Buying and distribution costs are included in determining our retail and corporate apparel clothing product gross margins. Our gross margin may not
	be comparable to other specialty retailers, as some companies exclude costs related to their distribution network from cost of goods sold while others, like us, include all or a portion of such costs
	in cost of goods sold and exclude them from SG&amp;A expenses. Distribution costs are not included in determining our rental services gross margin as these costs are included in SG&amp;A expenses.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Our
	total gross margin increased $125.8&nbsp;million, or 9.3%, to $1,484.4&nbsp;million for fiscal 2015 as compared to fiscal 2014. During fiscal 2015, as a result of our store rationalization
	program, we incurred $11.0&nbsp;million of inventory write-offs as well as a $4.8&nbsp;million charge related to discontinued rental product, both of which negatively impacted our gross margin
	results. During fiscal 2014, $33.5&nbsp;million of inventory valuation step up related to Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank and a $10.6&nbsp;million charge to rationalize our rental product to allow for more
	productive rental styles were incurred and negatively impacted our gross margin results.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Total
	retail segment gross margin increased $132.2&nbsp;million or 10.3% from fiscal 2014 to $1,414.1&nbsp;million in fiscal 2015. The dollar increase in gross margin was primarily driven by
	$98.0&nbsp;million of incremental gross margin generated by Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank as well as by higher sales from our Men's Wearhouse brand.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	For
	the retail segment, total gross margin as a percentage of related sales increased from 42.8% in fiscal 2014 to 43.5% in fiscal 2015 driven primarily by an increase in the rental services margin as
	well as a higher retail clothing product gross margin rate, which was negatively impacted last year by the inventory step up at Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Occupancy
	costs increased $60.0&nbsp;million primarily due to incremental Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank occupancy costs. Occupancy costs as a percentage of retail sales, which is relatively constant on a per
	store basis and includes store related rent, common area maintenance, utilities, repairs and maintenance, security, property taxes and depreciation, increased from 13.2% in fiscal 2014 to 14.0% in
	fiscal 2015, primarily due to deleveraging of occupancy costs at Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank as well as Jos&nbsp;A. Bank's occupancy costs being higher as a percentage of sales than our other brands.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Corporate
	apparel gross margin decreased $6.4&nbsp;million or 8.3% from fiscal 2014 to $70.3&nbsp;million in fiscal 2015. For the corporate apparel segment, total gross margin as a percentage of
	related sales decreased from 29.8% in fiscal 2014 to 28.9% in fiscal 2015 primarily due to unfavorable currency impacts at our UK operations.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Advertising Expense
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Advertising expense increased to $205.0&nbsp;million in fiscal 2015 from $168.3&nbsp;million in fiscal 2014, an increase of $36.7&nbsp;million
	or 21.8%. The increase was primarily due to incremental Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank advertising costs as well as increased advertising expense to support branding initiatives. As a percentage of total net
	sales, these expenses increased from 5.2% in fiscal 2014 to 5.9% in fiscal 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	40
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>

</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2227942Z10-K_HTM_BG11901A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>

</P>
<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<A NAME="FIS_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE_14"></A>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Selling, General and Administrative Expenses
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	SG&amp;A expenses decreased to $1,085.9&nbsp;million in fiscal 2015 from $1,116.8&nbsp;million in fiscal 2014, a decrease of $30.9&nbsp;million or
	2.8%. As a percentage of total net sales, these expenses decreased from 34.3% in fiscal 2014 to 31.1% in fiscal 2015. The components of this 3.2% net decrease in SG&amp;A expenses as a percentage of total
	net sales and the related dollar changes were as follows:
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="PADDING:0PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;WIDTH:80%;MARGIN-LEFT:10%;">

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	In
	the retail segment, SG&amp;A expenses as a percentage of related net sales decreased from 35.1% in fiscal 2014 to 31.5% in fiscal 2015. Retail segment SG&amp;A expenses decreased $26.9&nbsp;million
	primarily due to a decrease in acquisition, integration and other costs and litigation costs related to an arbitration award partially offset by a full year of operating expenses for Jos.&nbsp;A.
	Bank.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	In
	the corporate apparel segment, SG&amp;A expenses as a percentage of related net sales decreased from 25.2% in fiscal 2014 to 25.0% in fiscal 2015. Corporate apparel segment SG&amp;A expenses decreased
	$4.0&nbsp;million.
</FONT>
</P>

<!-- ZEQ.=4,SEQ=42,EFW="2227942",CP="TAILORED BRANDS INC",DN="1",CHK=784504,FOLIO='41',FILE='DISK129:[16ZAI1.16ZAI11901]DM11901A.;20',USER='SLYUBOM',CD='24-MAR-2016;12:55' -->
<!-- THIS IS THE END OF A COMPOSITION COMPONENT -->
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A NAME="A2227942Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_DO11901_1_42">
</A>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_BASECOLOR,"BLACK" -->
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_DEFAULTFONT,"FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;" -->
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TABLESHADECOLOR,"#CCEEFF" -->
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_STABLERULES,"BORDER-BOTTOM:SOLID #000000 1.0PT;" -->
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_DTABLERULES,"BORDER-BOTTOM:DOUBLE #000000 2.25PT;" -->
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_SCRTABLERULES,"BORDER-BOTTOM:SOLID #000000 1.0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;" -->
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_DCRTABLERULES,"BORDER-BOTTOM:DOUBLE #000000 2.25PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;" -->
<!-- PARA=JUSTIFY -->
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2227942Z10-K_HTM_BG11901A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Refer to
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Goodwill and Other Indefinite-Lived Intangible Assets
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	as discussed in "Critical Accounting Polices and Estimates" and
	Note&nbsp;3 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements for further details.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Asset Impairment Charges
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Non-cash asset impairment charges increased to $27.5&nbsp;million in fiscal 2015 as compared to $0.3&nbsp;million in fiscal 2014. The asset
	impairment charges in fiscal 2015 resulted primarily from our store rationalization program which identified approximately 250&nbsp;stores, which are
	expected to close in fiscal 2016. Refer to
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Impairment of Long-Lived Assets
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	as discussed in "Critical Accounting Polices and Estimates" and Note&nbsp;1
	of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements for further details.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Interest Expense
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Interest expense increased to $106.0&nbsp;million in fiscal 2015 from $66.0&nbsp;million in fiscal 2014, an increase of $40.0&nbsp;million or
	60.5%, due to incremental interest incurred on borrowings entered into in connection with the Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank acquisition.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Provision for Income Tax
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	In fiscal 2015, our effective income tax rate was (14.1%) and is lower than the U.S. statutory rate due to our overall net loss partially offset by
	the non-deductibility of the goodwill impairment charge, as discussed above. Our foreign jurisdictions in which we operate had taxable income, which requires us to provide for income tax,
	specifically, our operations in Canada and the United Kingdom. For fiscal 2015, the statutory tax rates in Canada and the United Kingdom were approximately 27% and 20%, respectively, which negatively
	impacted our effective tax rate due to the loss in the U.S. For fiscal 2015, tax expense for our operations in foreign jurisdictions totaled $8.9&nbsp;million.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Our
	income tax expense and effective income tax rate in future periods may be impacted by many factors, including our geographic mix of earnings and changes in tax laws. Currently, we expect our
	effective tax rate in future periods to be lower than the statutory United States combined federal and state tax rate based on the expected geographic mix of earnings.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	In
	addition, if our financial results in fiscal 2016 generate a loss or certain deferred tax liabilities decrease, we may need to establish a valuation allowance on our U.S. deferred tax assets, which
	could have a material impact on our financial condition and results of operations.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Net Loss Attributable to Common Shareholders
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	These factors resulted in a net loss attributable to common shareholders of $1,026.7&nbsp;million for fiscal 2015, a decrease of
	$1,026.3&nbsp;million from a net loss of $0.4&nbsp;million for fiscal 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	42
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>

<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS207" -->
</I>

</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#B54A63" SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	2014 Compared with 2013
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Net Sales
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Total net sales increased $779.3&nbsp;million, or 31.5%, to $3,252.5&nbsp;million for fiscal 2014 as compared to fiscal 2013.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Total
	retail sales increased $768.8&nbsp;million, or 34.5%, to $2,995.2&nbsp;million for fiscal 2014 as compared to fiscal 2013 due mainly to $684.0&nbsp;million of net sales from Jos.&nbsp;A.
	Bank since the date of acquisition as well as increases in retail clothing product revenues of $59.9&nbsp;million and rental services revenue of $21.8&nbsp;million from our other brands. The net
	increase is attributable to the following:
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="PADDING:0PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;WIDTH:80%;MARGIN-LEFT:10%;">
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
</FONT>

<TD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Decrease in net sales resulting from closed stores.

<!-- COMMAND=ADD_LINERULETXT,NOSHADE COLOR="#000000" SIZE="1.0PT" WIDTH="26%" ALIGN="LEFT" -->
<HR NOSHADE COLOR="#000000" SIZE="1.0PT" WIDTH="26%" ALIGN="LEFT">
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="PADDING:0PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;MARGIN-LEFT:10%;">
<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<SUP>
	(1)
</SUP>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Comparable
	sales percentages for Moores are calculated using Canadian dollars.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<SUP>
	(2)
</SUP>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Excludes
	Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank.
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Comparable
	sales for Men's Wearhouse, Moores and K&amp;G exclude the net sales of a store for any month of one period if the store was not open throughout the same month of the prior period and include
	e-commerce net sales. The inclusion of e-commerce net sales did not have a significant effect on comparable sales.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The
	increase at Men's Wearhouse resulted primarily from increased average unit retails and average transactions per store that more than offset decreased units sold per transaction. The increase at
	Moores was driven by increased average unit retails, units sold per transaction and average transactions per store. The increase at K&amp;G was due to increased units sold per transaction and average
	transactions per store which more than offset a decrease in average unit retails. At Men's Wearhouse, rental service comparable sales increased 6.4% primarily due to an increase in rental rates and a
	slight increase in unit rentals.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Total
	corporate apparel clothing product sales increased $10.6&nbsp;million to $257.4&nbsp;million for fiscal 2014 as compared to fiscal 2013. UK corporate apparel sales increased
	$7.7&nbsp;million due mainly to the impact of a stronger pound Sterling this year compared to last year. U.S. corporate apparel sales increased $2.9&nbsp;million due primarily to increased sales
	from existing customer programs.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Gross Margin
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Buying and distribution costs are included in determining our retail and corporate apparel clothing product gross margins. Our gross margin may not
	be comparable to other specialty retailers, as some companies exclude costs related to their distribution network from cost of goods sold while others, like us, include all or a portion of such costs
	in cost of goods sold and exclude them from SG&amp;A expenses. Distribution costs are not included in determining our rental services gross margin as these costs are included in SG&amp;A expenses.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	43
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=2,SEQ=44,EFW="2227942",CP="TAILORED BRANDS INC",DN="1",CHK=681855,FOLIO='43',FILE='DISK129:[16ZAI1.16ZAI11901]DO11901A.;17',USER='SLYUBOM',CD='24-MAR-2016;13:01' -->
<A NAME="A2227942Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_DO11901_1_44">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2227942Z10-K_HTM_BG11901A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Our
	total gross margin increased $269.6&nbsp;million, or 24.8%, to $1,358.6&nbsp;million for fiscal 2014 as compared to fiscal 2013. Total retail segment gross margin increased
	$266.4&nbsp;million or 26.2% from fiscal 2013 to $1,281.9&nbsp;million in fiscal 2014. The dollar increase in gross margin was primarily driven by $227.1&nbsp;million of gross margin generated
	by Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank as well as by higher sales from our other brands. As a result of the purchase price allocation for the Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank acquisition, a preliminary purchase accounting
	adjustment of $34.4&nbsp;million was recorded for the step up of inventory to its fair value. During fiscal 2014, $33.5&nbsp;million of the inventory valuation step up was recognized and
	negatively impacted gross margin results. We expect the remaining $0.9&nbsp;million of step up in inventory to be charged to cost of sales in the first half of fiscal 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	For
	the retail segment, total gross margin as a percentage of related sales decreased from 45.6% in fiscal 2013 to 42.8% in fiscal 2014 driven primarily by a lower gross margin as a percentage of
	sales for Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank, which includes the recognition of the inventory step up at Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank, partially offset by a higher retail clothing product gross margin rate at our other
	brands. In addition, retail segment gross margin was impacted by a decrease in the rental services gross margin rate primarily due to a $10.6&nbsp;million charge to rationalize our rental product to
	allow for more productive rental styles, as well as increased royalty expenses.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Occupancy
	costs increased $104.6&nbsp;million primarily due to Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank occupancy costs. Occupancy costs as a percentage of retail sales, which is relatively constant on a per store basis
	and includes store related rent, common area maintenance, utilities, repairs and maintenance, security, property taxes and depreciation, increased slightly from 13.1% in fiscal 2013 to 13.2% in fiscal
	2014, primarily due to the impact of Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank's occupancy costs, which are higher as a percentage of sales than our other brands.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Corporate
	apparel gross margin increased $3.2&nbsp;million or 4.4% from fiscal 2013 to $76.7&nbsp;million in fiscal 2014. For the corporate apparel segment, total gross margin as a percentage of
	related sales was flat at 29.8% for both fiscal 2013 and 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Advertising Expense
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Advertising expense increased to $168.3&nbsp;million in fiscal 2014 from $101.1&nbsp;million in fiscal 2013, an increase of $67.2&nbsp;million
	or 66.5%. The increase was primarily driven by
	Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank advertising costs as well as advertising expense related to the rollout of Joseph Abboud merchandise. As a percentage of total net sales, these expenses increased from 4.1% in
	fiscal 2013 to 5.2% in fiscal 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	44
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=3,SEQ=45,EFW="2227942",CP="TAILORED BRANDS INC",DN="1",CHK=617221,FOLIO='44',FILE='DISK129:[16ZAI1.16ZAI11901]DO11901A.;17',USER='SLYUBOM',CD='24-MAR-2016;13:01' -->
<A NAME="A2227942Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_DO11901_1_45">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2227942Z10-K_HTM_BG11901A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Selling, General and Administrative Expenses
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	SG&amp;A expenses increased to $1,116.8&nbsp;million in fiscal 2014 from $846.6&nbsp;million in fiscal 2013, an increase of $270.2&nbsp;million or
	31.9%. The dollar increase in SG&amp;A expenses was driven by an increase in expenses related to acquisition, integration and other costs primarily related to Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank, a licensee arbitration
	award related to JA&nbsp;Holding, other cost reduction initiatives, as well as Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank operating expenses, which includes amortization of intangible assets recorded in connection with
	the Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank acquisition. As a percentage of total net sales, these expenses increased from 34.2% in fiscal 2013 to 34.3% in fiscal 2014. The components of the changes in SG&amp;A expenses as a
	percentage of total net sales and the related dollar changes were as follows:
</FONT>
</P>
<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<A NAME="FIS_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE_17"></A>

	brands.

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	In
	the retail segment, SG&amp;A expenses as a percentage of related net sales decreased from 35.2% in fiscal 2013 to 35.1% in fiscal 2014. Retail segment SG&amp;A expenses increased $267.5&nbsp;million
	primarily due to acquisition, integration and other costs, costs related to the JA&nbsp;Holding licensee arbitration award and operating expenses for Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank, which includes amortization
	of intangible assets recorded in connection with the Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank acquisition and other cost reduction initiatives.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	In
	the corporate apparel segment, SG&amp;A expenses as a percentage of related net sales remained flat at 25.2% in both fiscal 2013 and 2014. Corporate apparel segment SG&amp;A expenses increased
	$2.7&nbsp;million primarily due to higher UK operating expenses driven by the impact of a stronger pound Sterling this year compared to last year.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Interest Expense
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Interest expense increased to $66.0&nbsp;million in fiscal 2014 from $3.2&nbsp;million in fiscal 2013 primarily due to interest expense on
	borrowings entered into in connection with the Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank acquisition.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	45
</FONT>
</P>

<!-- ZEQ.=4,SEQ=46,EFW="2227942",CP="TAILORED BRANDS INC",DN="1",CHK=686646,FOLIO='45',FILE='DISK129:[16ZAI1.16ZAI11901]DO11901A.;17',USER='SLYUBOM',CD='24-MAR-2016;13:01' -->
<A NAME="A2227942Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_DO11901_1_46">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2227942Z10-K_HTM_BG11901A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Provision for Income Tax
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Our effective income tax rate increased from 33.6% for fiscal 2013 to 101.8% for fiscal 2014 primarily due to an increase in permanent items as a
	percent of pre-tax earnings, mainly consisting of non-deductible transaction costs related to the Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank acquisition, resulting in our effective tax rate being higher than the statutory
	United States combined federal and state tax rate. Furthermore, the foreign jurisdictions in which we operate had profitability which require us to provide for income tax, specifically, our operations
	in Canada and the United Kingdom. For fiscal 2014, the statutory tax rates in Canada and the United Kingdom were approximately 26% and 20%, respectively, which favorably impacted our effective tax
	rate. For fiscal 2014, tax expense for our operations in foreign jurisdictions totaled $11.5&nbsp;million. Lastly, our effective income tax rate was also favorably impacted by amortizable goodwill
	related to a prior acquisition.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Thus,
	the combination of tax expense being recorded on U.S. activity (due mainly to the non-deductible transaction costs), and for tax expense from our foreign operations, coupled with low book income
	results in a high effective tax rate for fiscal 2014 compared to fiscal 2013.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Our
	income tax expense and effective income tax rate in future periods may be impacted by many factors, including our geographic mix of earnings and changes in tax laws. Currently, we expect our
	effective tax rate in future periods to be lower than the statutory United States combined federal and state tax rate based on the expected geographic mix of earnings.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Net (Loss) Earnings Attributable to Common Shareholders
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	These factors resulted in a net loss attributable to common shareholders of $0.4&nbsp;million for fiscal 2014, a decrease of $84.2&nbsp;million
	from net earnings of $83.8&nbsp;million for fiscal 2013.
</FONT>
</P>
</EFX_RESULTS_OF_OPERATIONS>
<EFX_LIQUIDITY_CAPITAL>
<A NAME="FIS_LIQUIDITY_CAPITAL"></A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS207" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#B54A63" SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Liquidity and Capital Resources
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	At January&nbsp;30, 2016 and January&nbsp;31, 2015, cash and cash equivalents totaled $30.0&nbsp;million and $62.3&nbsp;million,
	respectively. At January&nbsp;30, 2016, cash and cash equivalents held by foreign subsidiaries totaled $27.0&nbsp;million. Under current tax laws and regulations, if cash and cash equivalents held
	outside the U.S. are repatriated to the U.S., in certain circumstances we may be subject to additional U.S. income taxes and foreign withholding taxes. We currently do not intend to repatriate amounts
	held by foreign subsidiaries.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	We
	had working capital of $723.6&nbsp;million and $752.3&nbsp;million at January&nbsp;30, 2016 and January&nbsp;31, 2015, respectively. Our primary sources of working capital are cash flows
	from operations and available borrowings under our financing arrangements, as described below.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	On
	June&nbsp;18, 2014, we entered into a term loan credit agreement, that provides for a senior secured term loan in the aggregate principal amount of $1.1&nbsp;billion (the "Term Loan"), and a
	$500.0&nbsp;million asset-based revolving credit agreement (the "ABL Facility", and together with the Term Loan, the "Credit Facilities") with certain of our U.S. subsidiaries and Moores the Suit
	People&nbsp;Inc., one of our Canadian subsidiaries, as co-borrowers. In addition, on June&nbsp;18, 2014, we issued $600.0&nbsp;million in aggregate principal amount of 7.00% Senior Notes due
	2022 (the "Senior Notes").
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The
	Credit Facilities and the Senior Notes contain customary non-financial and financial covenants, including fixed charge coverage ratios, total leverage ratios and secured leverage ratios, as well
	as a restriction on our ability to pay dividends on our common stock in excess of $10.0&nbsp;million per quarter. Since entering into these financing arrangements and as of January&nbsp;30, 2016,
	our total leverage ratio and secured leverage ratio were above the maximums specified in the agreements, which was anticipated when we entered into these arrangements. As a result, we are currently
	subject to certain additional restrictions, including limitations on our ability to make acquisitions and incur additional indebtedness. As of January&nbsp;30, 2016, we believe we will be in
	compliance with all of the non-financial and financial covenants
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	46
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=5,SEQ=47,EFW="2227942",CP="TAILORED BRANDS INC",DN="1",CHK=671825,FOLIO='46',FILE='DISK129:[16ZAI1.16ZAI11901]DO11901A.;17',USER='SLYUBOM',CD='24-MAR-2016;13:01' -->
<A NAME="A2227942Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_DO11901_1_47">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2227942Z10-K_HTM_BG11901A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	by
	the end of fiscal 2017 which will result in the elimination of these additional restrictions. In addition, in accordance with the terms of the Credit Facilities, we have an obligation to make a
	mandatory excess cash flow prepayment offer of $35.5&nbsp;million to the Term Loan lenders by April&nbsp;29, 2016. Our lenders have the option to decline their respective portions of the
	prepayment.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	We
	used the net proceeds from the Term Loan, the offering of the Senior Notes and the net proceeds from $340.0&nbsp;million drawn on the ABL Facility to pay the approximately $1.8&nbsp;billion
	purchase price for the acquisition of Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank and to repay all of our obligations under our Third Amended and Restated Credit Agreement, dated as of April&nbsp;12, 2013 (as amended the
	"Previous Credit Agreement"), including $95.0&nbsp;million outstanding under the Previous Credit Agreement as well as settlement of the then existing interest rate swap. The loans under the ABL
	Facility were subsequently repaid in full promptly following the closing of the Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank acquisition using the cash acquired from Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS207" -->
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#B54A63" SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Credit Facilities
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The Term Loan is guaranteed, jointly and severally, by certain of our U.S. subsidiaries and will mature on June&nbsp;18, 2021. The interest rate on
	the Term Loan is based on the 3-month LIBOR rate, which was approximately 0.61% at January&nbsp;30, 2016. However, the Term Loan interest rate is subject to a LIBOR floor of 1% per annum, plus the
	applicable margin which is currently 3.50%, resulting in a total interest rate of 4.50% at January&nbsp;30, 2016. To minimize the impact of changes in interest rates on our interest payments under
	the Term Loan, in January 2015, we entered into an interest rate swap agreement to swap variable-rate interest payments for fixed-rate interest payments on a notional amount of $520.0&nbsp;million,
	effective in February 2015. The interest rate swap agreement matures in August 2018 and has periodic interest settlements. Under this interest rate swap agreement, we receive a floating rate based on
	the 3-month LIBOR rate and pay a fixed rate of 5.03% (including the applicable margin of 3.50%) on the outstanding notional amount.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	On
	April&nbsp;7, 2015, we entered into Incremental Facility Agreement No.&nbsp;1 (the "Incremental Agreement") resulting in a refinancing of $400.0&nbsp;million aggregate principal amount of our
	Term Loan from a variable rate to a fixed rate of 5.0% per annum. The Incremental Agreement did not impact the total amount borrowed under the Term Loan, the maturity date of the Term Loan of
	June&nbsp;18, 2021, or collateral and guarantees under the existing Term Loan.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	As
	a result of the interest rate swap and the Incremental Agreement, we have converted a majority of the variable interest rate under the Term Loan to a fixed rate and, as of January&nbsp;30, 2016,
	the Term Loan had a weighted average interest rate of 4.90%.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The
	ABL Facility provides for a senior secured revolving credit facility of $500.0&nbsp;million, with possible future increases to $650.0&nbsp;million under an expansion feature that matures on
	June&nbsp;18, 2019 and is guaranteed, jointly and severally, by certain of our U.S. subsidiaries. The ABL Facility has several borrowing and interest rate options including the following indices:
	(i)&nbsp;adjusted LIBOR, (ii)&nbsp;Canadian Dollar Offered Rate, (iii)&nbsp;Canadian prime rate or (iv)&nbsp;an alternate base rate (equal to the greater of the prime rate, the federal funds
	effective rate plus 0.5% or adjusted LIBOR for a one-month period plus 1.0%). Advances under the ABL Facility bear interest at a rate per annum using the applicable indices plus a varying interest
	rate margin of up to 2.00%. The ABL Facility also provides for fees applicable
	to amounts available to be drawn under outstanding letters of credit which range from 1.50% to 2.00%, and a fee on unused commitments which ranges from 0.25% to 0.375%. As of January&nbsp;30, 2016,
	there were no borrowings outstanding under the ABL Facility.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The
	obligations under the Credit Facilities are secured on a senior basis by a first priority lien on substantially all of the assets of the Company, certain of its U.S. subsidiaries and, in the case
	of the ABL Facility, Moores The Suit People Inc. The Credit Facilities and the related guarantees and security interests granted thereunder are senior secured obligations of, and will rank equally
	with all present and future senior indebtedness of, the Company, the co-borrowers and the respective guarantors.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	47
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	We
	utilize letters of credit primarily to secure inventory purchases and as collateral for workers compensation claims. At January&nbsp;30, 2016, letters of credit totaling approximately
	$25.5&nbsp;million were issued and outstanding. Borrowings available under the ABL Facility as of January&nbsp;30, 2016 were $420.9&nbsp;million.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS207" -->
</I>
</B>

<FONT COLOR="#B54A63" SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Senior Notes
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The Senior Notes are guaranteed, jointly and severally, on an unsecured basis by certain of our U.S. subsidiaries. The Senior Notes and the related
	guarantees are senior unsecured obligations of the Company and the guarantors, respectively, and will rank equally with all of the Company's and each guarantor's present and future senior
	indebtedness. The Senior Notes will mature on July&nbsp;1, 2022. Interest on the Senior Notes are payable on January&nbsp;1 and July&nbsp;1 of each year. Payments began January&nbsp;1, 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	We
	may redeem some or all of the Senior Notes at any time on or after July&nbsp;1, 2017 at the redemption prices set forth in the indenture governing the Senior Notes. At any time prior to
	July&nbsp;1, 2017, we will have the option to redeem some or all of the Senior Notes at a redemption price of 100% of the principal amount of the Senior Notes to be redeemed, plus a "make-whole"
	premium and accrued and unpaid interest, if any, to the date of redemption. We may also redeem up to a maximum of 35% of the original aggregate principal amount of the Senior Notes with the proceeds
	of certain equity offerings prior to July&nbsp;1, 2017 at a redemption price of 107% of the principal amount of the Senior Notes plus accrued and unpaid interest, if any. Upon the occurrence of
	certain specific changes of control, we may be required to offer to purchase the Senior Notes at 101% of their aggregate principal amount plus accrued and unpaid interest thereon to the date of
	purchase.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	We
	had entered into a registration rights agreement regarding the Senior Notes pursuant to which we agreed, among other things, to use our commercially reasonable efforts to consummate an exchange
	offer of the Senior Notes for substantially identical notes registered under the Securities Act of 1933, as amended, on or before July&nbsp;13, 2015. On June&nbsp;24, 2015, the exchange offer was
	completed.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS207" -->
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#B54A63" SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Cash Provided by Operating Activities
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Net cash provided by operating activities was $131.7&nbsp;million and $94.8&nbsp;million for 2015 and 2014, respectively. The
	$36.9&nbsp;million increase was driven by higher net earnings, after adjusting for non-cash items including goodwill, intangible and other asset impairment charges, partially offset by the impact of
	working capital items. Unfavorable changes in working capital include an increase in inventories, primarily due to higher inventory levels from lower sales and increased purchases of rental product
	partially offset by favorable fluctuations in accounts payable, accrued expenses and other current liabilities.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Net
	cash provided by operating activities was $94.8&nbsp;million and $188.9&nbsp;million for 2014 and 2013, respectively. The $94.1&nbsp;million decrease is primarily the result of a decrease in
	net earnings driven by acquisition and integration costs related to Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank, interest expense on our indebtedness, and an arbitration award related to JA&nbsp;Holding, as well as changes
	in working capital, primarily related to fluctuations in accounts payable, accrued expenses and other current liabilities.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS207" -->
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#B54A63" SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Cash Used in Investing Activities
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Net cash used in investing activities was $112.9&nbsp;million and $1,587.7&nbsp;million for 2015 and 2014, respectively. The
	$1,474.8&nbsp;million decrease was primarily driven by last year's acquisition of Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank. The increase in capital expenditures in 2015 compared to 2014 was primarily due to integration
	projects for Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank as well as store remodels, openings and/or relocations.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Net
	cash used in investing activities was $1,587.7&nbsp;million and $199.0&nbsp;million for 2014 and 2013, respectively. The $1,388.7&nbsp;million increase in cash used in investing activities
	was primarily driven by the acquisition of Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank. Our capital expenditures in 2014 and 2013 relate to costs incurred for stores opened,
</FONT>
</P>

	Net cash used in financing activities was $46.8&nbsp;million for 2015 compared to net cash provided by financing activities of
	$1,500.9&nbsp;million for 2014. The net change of $1,547.7&nbsp;million was primarily driven by last year's proceeds on our Term Loan and issuance of Senior Notes for the acquisition of
	Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank.

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">

	cash provided by financing activities was $1,500.9&nbsp;million for 2014 compared to net cash used in financing activities of $82.9&nbsp;million for 2013. The net change of
	$1,583.8&nbsp;million was primarily driven by borrowings on our Term Loan and issuance of the Senior Notes for the acquisition of Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank. Cash outflows from financing activities consist
	primarily of repayment of borrowings under our ABL Facility and previous term loan, payment of deferred financing costs related to our Credit Facilities and cash dividend payments.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
	Share repurchase program
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#151;In March 2013, the Board of Directors (the "Board") approved a $200.0&nbsp;million share repurchase program for our common stock, which
	amended and replaced our then existing share repurchase program authorized by the Board in January 2011. At January&nbsp;30, 2016, the remaining balance available under the Board's March 2013
	authorization was $48.0&nbsp;million. During fiscal 2015, no shares were repurchased in open market transactions under the Board's March 2013 authorization.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	In
	July 2013, we entered into an accelerated share repurchase agreement ("ASR Agreement") with J.P.&nbsp;Morgan Securities LLC ("JPMorgan"), as agent for JPMorgan Chase Bank, National Association,
	London Branch, to purchase $100.0&nbsp;million of our common stock. A total of 2,653,287&nbsp;shares were repurchased under the ASR Agreement and immediately retired. In addition to the ASR
	Agreement, during fiscal 2013, 1,489,318&nbsp;shares at a cost of $52.0&nbsp;million were repurchased in open market transactions under the Board's March 2013 authorization.
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
	Dividends
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#151;Cash dividends paid were approximately $35.0&nbsp;million, $34.8&nbsp;million and $35.5&nbsp;million during fiscal 2015, 2014 and 2013,
	respectively. In fiscal 2015, 2014 and 2013, a dividend of $0.18 per share was declared in each quarter, for an annual dividend of $0.72 per share, respectively. The cash dividend of $0.18 per share
	declared by the Board in January 2016 is payable on March&nbsp;25, 2016 to shareholders of record on March&nbsp;15, 2016.
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS207" -->
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#B54A63" SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Future sources and uses of cash
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Our primary uses of cash are to finance working capital requirements of our operations and to repay our indebtedness. In addition, we will use cash
	to fund capital expenditures, income taxes, integration costs associated with Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank, costs related to our store rationalization and profit improvement programs
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	49
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=8,SEQ=50,EFW="2227942",CP="TAILORED BRANDS INC",DN="1",CHK=945310,FOLIO='49',FILE='DISK129:[16ZAI1.16ZAI11901]DO11901A.;17',USER='SLYUBOM',CD='24-MAR-2016;13:01' -->
<A NAME="A2227942Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_DO11901_1_50">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2227942Z10-K_HTM_BG11901A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	including
	lease termination payments, dividend payments, operating leases and various other commitments and obligations, as they arise.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Capital
	expenditures are anticipated to be in the range of $110.0 to $120.0&nbsp;million for 2016. This amount includes the anticipated costs to open 166&nbsp;shops within Macy's stores, 15 to 20
	Men's Wearhouse stores, three Moores stores, two Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank stores and two K&amp;G stores and to expand and/or relocate approximately 8 to 12 existing Men's Wearhouse stores, four to eight
	existing Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank stores and one existing K&amp;G store. The average cost (excluding telecommunications and point-of-sale equipment and inventory) of opening a new store, which does not include
	shops within Macy's stores, is expected to be approximately $0.5&nbsp;million in 2016. The balance of the capital expenditures for 2016 will be used for integration projects related to
	Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank, distribution facilities, point-of-sale and other computer equipment and systems, store remodeling, and investment in other corporate assets. The actual amount of future capital
	expenditures will depend in part on the number of new stores opened and the terms on which new stores are leased and the timing of our Jos.&nbsp;A. Bank integration projects, as well as on industry
	trends consistent with our anticipated operating plans.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Additionally,
	market conditions may produce attractive opportunities for us to make acquisitions. Any such acquisitions may be undertaken as an alternative to opening new stores. We may use cash on
	hand, together with cash flow from operations, borrowings under our Credit Facilities and issuances of debt or equity securities, to take advantage of any acquisition opportunities.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Current
	and future domestic and global economic conditions could negatively affect our future operating results as well as our existing cash and cash equivalents balances. In addition, conditions in
	the financial markets could limit our access to further capital resources, if needed, and could increase associated costs. We believe based on our current business plan that our existing cash and cash
	flows from operations and availability under our ABL Facility will be sufficient to fund our operating cash requirements, repayment of current indebtedness, planned store openings, relocations and
	remodels, other capital expenditures, and integration costs associated with Jos.&nbsp;A.&nbsp;Bank.
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT SIZE=2>

</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#B54A63" SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Contractual Obligations
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	As of January&nbsp;30, 2016, we are obligated to make cash payments in connection with our long-term debt, non-cancelable operating leases and
	other contractual obligations in the amounts listed below. In addition, we utilize letters of credit primarily for inventory purchases and as collateral for workers compensation claims. At
	January&nbsp;30, 2016, letters of credit totaling approximately $25.5&nbsp;million were issued and outstanding.
</FONT>
</P>

	Includes
	interest payments of $94.8&nbsp;million within one year, $196.5&nbsp;million between one and three years, $169.1&nbsp;million
	between four and five years and $93.1&nbsp;million beyond five years, at current interest rates including the impact of active interest rate swaps. The payments due by period do not consider amounts
	which may become payable under the excess cash flow provision of our Term Loan. See Notes&nbsp;6 and 16 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements for additional information.

<A NAME="A2227942Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_DO11901_1_51">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2227942Z10-K_HTM_BG11901A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="PADDING:0PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;MARGIN-LEFT:10%;">
<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<SUP>
	(2)
</SUP>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	We
	lease retail business locations, office and warehouse facilities and equipment under various non-cancelable operating leases. See
	Note&nbsp;18 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements for additional information.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<SUP>
	(3)
</SUP>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Other
	contractual obligations consist primarily of minimum payments under our agreement with Macy's to operate shops within Macy's stores, our
	agreement with Vera Wang that gives us the exclusive right to "Black by Vera Wang" tuxedo products, our partnership with Kenneth Cole and our marketing agreement with David's Bridal, Inc. Pursuant to
	our marketing agreement with David's Bridal, Inc., there are performance conditions that may impact future payments. These potential future payments are not included in the table above as such amounts
	are not readily determinable.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<SUP>
	(4)
</SUP>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Excluded
	from the table above is $22.0&nbsp;million related to uncertain tax positions. These amounts are not included due to our inability
	to predict the timing of the settlement of these amounts. Refer to Note&nbsp;7 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements for additional information.
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	In
	the normal course of business, we issue purchase orders to vendors/suppliers for merchandise. The purchase orders represent executory contracts requiring performance by the vendors/suppliers,
	including the delivery of the merchandise prior to a specified cancellation date and compliance with product specifications, quality standards and other requirements. In the event of the vendor's
	failure to meet the agreed upon terms and conditions, we may cancel the order.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS207" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#B54A63" SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Off-Balance Sheet Arrangements
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Other than the non-cancelable operating leases, other contractual obligations and letters of credit discussed above, we do not have any off-balance
	sheet arrangements that are material to our financial position or results of operations.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS207" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#B54A63" SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Inflation
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	We believe the impact of inflation on the results of operations during the periods presented has been minimal. However, there can be no assurance
	that our business will not be affected by inflation in the future.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS207" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#B54A63" SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Critical Accounting Policies and Estimates
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The preparation of our consolidated financial statements requires the appropriate application of accounting policies in accordance with generally
	accepted accounting principles. In many instances, this also requires management to make estimates and assumptions about future events that affect the amounts and disclosures included in our financial
	statements. We base our
	estimates on historical experience and various assumptions that we believe are reasonable under our current business model. However, because future events and conditions and their effects cannot be
	determined with certainty, actual results will differ from our estimates and such differences could be material to our financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Our
	accounting policies are described in Note&nbsp;1 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements. We consistently apply these policies and periodically evaluate the reasonableness of our estimates
	in light of actual events. Historically, we have found our accounting policies to be appropriate and our estimates and assumptions reasonable. Our critical accounting policies, which are those most
	significant to the presentation of our financial position and results of operations and those that require significant judgment or complex estimates by management, are discussed below.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
	Revenue Recognition
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#151;Clothing product revenue is recognized at the time of sale and delivery of merchandise, net of actual sales returns and a provision for
	estimated sales returns. For e-commerce sales, revenue is recognized at the time we estimate the customer receives the product, which incorporates shipping terms and estimated delivery times. Revenues
	from rental, alteration and other services are recognized upon completion of the services. Amounts related to shipping and handling revenues billed to customers are recorded in net sales, and the
	related shipping and handling costs are recorded in cost of sales.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	51
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>

<FONT SIZE=2>
<A NAME="A2227942Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_DQ11901_1_52">
</A>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_BASECOLOR,"BLACK" -->
